    Physics view of energy minimum btranslaters to the placement of memory in a stable and "low" energy state 

What happens if we have  more than 2 memories, becomes very hard to map a partial memory 

Each memory has a local min 
- Need to supply random state vector s to recover closest memory encoded in the network 
- E(s) = - 0.5 SUM(w(ij)s(i)s(j)) - SUM(b(i)s(i))
    - b(i) is the bias term that is usually zero but can be used to control activation threshhold
- First, define local field h(i)
    store current state in s(old)
    chose a random neuron (i) and compute local field h = SUM(w(ij)s(i) + b(i))
    update s(i)' with sign h(s(i)) 
    update network state s <-- s' (only if neuron i changes)

    check for convergence
        - if hamming distance is 0 between all consecutive pairs 
        - if current state matches a stored memory pattern (hammind distance is 0)
    

    Hamming distance H[a,b] = SUM(Indicator(a is not equal to b))
    if H = 0, states are identical 

